{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/compression-stockings/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"fbc6929c-909c-5ad7-8267-8b7b8ffd1599","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 09ab8ffa-b163-4ac5-86eb-e6ddc62fdc15 --><h2>What are compression stockings?</h2><!-- end field 09ab8ffa-b163-4ac5-86eb-e6ddc62fdc15 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 01bafdec-a5d7-453b-88e5-2aa585d847d4 --><!-- begin field b3aa5ff3-5909-45af-841e-c3467a9b28ce --><ul><li>Compression stockings are useful for treating conditions associated with chronic venous insufficiency, including varicose veins, venous ulcers, venous eczema, post-thrombotic syndrome and lipodermatosclerosis.</li><li>They provide graduated pressure from the distal to the proximal portion of the leg and increase venous blood flow by improving the action of the calf-muscle pump.</li><li>They vary in degree of compression measured at the ankle (class), length (below knee or thigh length), colour, and whether they enclose the whole foot or stop just before the toes (closed or open toe).</li><li>Stockings prescribed in primary care follow the British standard for class of compression:<ul><li>Class 1 stockings (light compression) exert a pressure of 14–17 mmHg.</li><li>Class 2 stockings (medium compression) exert a pressure of 18–24 mmHg.</li><li>Class 3 stockings (high compression) exert a pressure of 25–35 mmHg.</li></ul></li><li>Hospital departments may provide European standard stockings, which provide a stronger degree of compression for each class. For example, class 2 in the European standard provides a pressure of 23–32 mmHg.</li><li>Graduated compression tights are also available but cannot be prescribed on the NHS — they can be bought from pharmacies or directly from the manufacturer.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/compression-stockings/references/\">SIGN, 2010</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/compression-stockings/references/\">Lim, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/compression-stockings/references/\">Wounds UK, 2015</a>]</p><!-- end field b3aa5ff3-5909-45af-841e-c3467a9b28ce --><!-- end item 01bafdec-a5d7-453b-88e5-2aa585d847d4 -->","topic":{"id":"6a31699b-4df2-5fb2-8158-3a0e92a8e7eb","topicId":"eb2600a9-8943-4252-938e-032dfe5933f8","topicName":"Compression stockings","slug":"compression-stockings","lastRevised":"Last revised in September 2018","chapters":[{"id":"73f1a203-62e9-5aaf-b61e-ce7ebc201ae9","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"62893c7c-d825-559e-8358-b33ac4901ace","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"37f8eb6d-20ce-5efc-94ce-4c275d3ff85f","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"ec6ed577-cc8f-51fd-ba58-0f919d0e34e9","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"02f5dd79-4069-5407-9f12-9ace79f0d8ae","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"1cc5a10b-49b4-5a51-a2c4-39e69eb25fff","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"7c4737af-948e-5161-a85f-61b9dc1d690d","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7266bc91-abea-547a-b2a5-33d5bfcb2ba0","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"fe2bb32a-ce7c-5fea-aa2a-0f6ad7a6caed","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"f06c1cdf-db2a-522a-8567-6906fc119556","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"4cd1b343-2088-5fb9-979b-7d3b8ae5d1d8","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"3084c836-9e9c-59b9-bcab-3382b751f320","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"